[normal])
[normal]The ILO promotes the employability and employment of women and men with disabilities through its standards on discrimination and disability, the development of knowledge on good practice in training and employment, policy advisory and advocacy work, and do
[normal]nor-funded technical cooperation projects. 
[normal]The key elements of a rights-based approach 
[normal]–
[normal] equality of opportunity, equal treatment and non-discrimination 
[normal]–
[normal] are contained in ILO Conventions concerning employment in general and persons with disabilities in p
[normal]articular. Chief among the standards used by the ILO to promote the rights and opportunities of disabled persons are the 
[normal]Discrimination (Employment and Occupation) Convention, 1958 (No. 111)
[normal], the 
[normal]Equal Remuneration Convention, 1951 (No. 100)
[normal], and the 
[normal]Vocat
[normal]ional Rehabilitation and Employment (Disabled Persons) Convention, 1983 (No. 159)
[normal], as well as the 
[normal]ILO Code of Practice on Managing Disability in the Workplace of 2002
[normal].
[normal]In November 2012, the ILO Governing Body welcomed the commitment to include people with 
[normal]disabilities in all areas of work of the ILO through a Disability Inclusion Initiative.
